# Lua config

Config lives in `~/.config/nvim/init.lua` (or `init.vim` ‚Äî pick one, not both).
Everything a vimrc does (@vim/config) has a Lua twin through the `vim` global;
`:lua {chunk}` runs Lua inline, `:luafile {f}` sources a file, and `nvim -l {f}`
runs one headlessly (@vim/script). Legacy vimscript still works everywhere ‚Äî
Lua is additive, not a replacement.

## Options

| Lua | Vimscript twin |
|-----|----------------|
| `vim.opt.number = true` | `:set number` |
| `vim.opt.shiftwidth = 2` | `:set shiftwidth=2` |
| `vim.opt.path:append('**')` | `:set path+=**` (also `:prepend`, `:remove`) |
| `vim.opt_local.spell = true` | `:setlocal spell` |
| `vim.o.name` / `vim.bo` / `vim.wo` | raw option values ‚Äî global / buffer / window |
| `vim.g.mapleader = ' '` | `:let g:mapleader` (`vim.b`, `vim.w`, `vim.env` likewise) |

`vim.opt` wraps list/map options as Lua tables (`vim.opt.listchars = {tab='¬ª '}`);
`vim.o` is the plain value. Either works for booleans and numbers.

## Mappings

```lua
vim.keymap.set('n', '<leader>w', ':write<CR>')            -- :nnoremap
vim.keymap.set('i', 'jk', '<Esc>')                        -- :inoremap
vim.keymap.set('n', '<leader>f', function() print('hi') end,
  { desc = 'described', silent = true, buffer = 0 })
```

Non-recursive by default (add `remap = true` to opt out) ‚Äî the opposite spelling
of `:map` vs `:noremap`. An `{rhs}` can be a Lua function directly; `desc` shows
in `:map` listings. `vim.keymap.del('n', lhs)` removes.

## Autocommands

```lua
local grp = vim.api.nvim_create_augroup('fmt', { clear = true })
vim.api.nvim_create_autocmd('BufWritePre', {
  group = grp, pattern = '*.go',
  callback = function() vim.lsp.buf.format() end,
})
```

`callback` takes a Lua function; use `command = '‚Ä¶'` for an ex string instead.
Events and patterns are the same as `:autocmd` (@vim/config).

## Escape hatches

| Call | Reaches |
|------|---------|
| `vim.cmd('wincmd p')` / `vim.cmd.wincmd('p')` | any ex command (@vim/ex) |
| `vim.fn.expand('%:p')` | any vimscript function |
| `vim.api.nvim_*` | the structured editor API (@nvim/api) |

Modules under `~/.config/nvim/lua/` load with `require('name')` ‚Äî the standard
way to split a config into files.
